TY  - JOUR
AB  - Competition is cutthroat when an industry experiences subnormal earnings over a considerable period. This situation arises where excess capacity coincides with inability of producers to control production and prices. The experience of the cotton textile industry supports the view that cutthroat competition tends in time to correct itself. The excess capacity which developed in this industry around 1923 was substantially eliminated by 1937. Under certain conditions, however, it is quite possible for cutthroat competition to continue indefinitely. This possibility arises chiefly from the imperfection of the labor market.
