TY  - JOUR
AB  - In this paper various characteristics of savings deposits are studied in order to clarify the functions of these deposits. (1) In the late 1920's many deposits were withdrawn for the purchase of stocks and other investments. During the 1930's, as a rule, deposits were not used for current spending on consumption to the extent commonly supposed. In one depressed area, however, spending and unemployment were the main reasons for withdrawal. (2) The activity of savings deposits is marked by sharp seasonal fluctuations, but the annual rate of turnover is more stable than that for demand deposits. Medium-sized balances ($400-800) are the most active. (3) The data indicate that over 40 per cent of accounts are closed before becoming a year old. Older and larger accounts, however, make up a large part of total deposits. (4) These data emphasize the need for a time period in the definition of savings, since many deposits are used for non-current spending. The use of savings deposits as investments, however, seems to be increasing.
